===Etymology===
1580, from {{etyl|frm|en}} {{m|frm|massacre}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{m|fro|macacre|macacre, macecle|slaughterhouse, butchery}}, from {{etyl|ML.|en}} {{m|en|mazacrium||massacre, slaughter, killing”, also “the head of a newly killed stag}}, from {{etyl|gml|en}} {{m|gml|*matskelen||to massacre}} (compare {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|metzeln||massacre}}), frequentive of {{m|gml|matsken|matsken, matzgen|to cut, hew}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*maitaną||to cut}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*mei-||small}}. Akin to {{etyl|goh|-}} {{m|goh|meizan||to cut}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{m|nl|matsen||to maul, kill}}, dialectal {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|metzgern||to butcher, kill}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{m|de|metzgen||to cull, kill, slaughter cattle}}, {{m|de|Metzger||a butcher}}, {{m|de|Metzelei||massacre}}, {{etyl|got|-}} {{m|got|𐌼𐌰𐌹𐍄𐌰𐌽||to cut}}. Alternatively, the Old French may have been derived from the verb {{m|fr|macacrer}}, {{m|fr|macacler}}, from a {{etyl|VL.|en}} *''matteuculāre'', from *''matteuca'', from {{etyl|LL.|en}} ''mattea''. See also the modern French term {{m|fr|massacrer}}.

